ials took place at Connecticut College on the Thames River. Only this time instead of sorcery it was Zionism; instead of punishing in the name of God's law it was in the name of anti-hate speech and inclusive excellence; instead of young teenage girls leading the hysteria it was college-aged social warriors stampeding 200 professors into sacrificing one of their colleagues, and thereby contributing to a wave of administration-promoted hate-speech at their college.The Pessin affair offers us a case study in a tendency towards "public shaming" that not only deeply compromises the integrity of academia, but increasingly spreads to many aspects of our society, so susceptible to media-driven feeding frenzies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aEducation, HigherxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aHate speechzUnited States. 0aZionismzUnited StatesxPublic opinion. 7aRELIGION / Religious Intolerance, Persecution & Conflict.2bisacsh  aAcademia.  aBDS.  aConnecticut College.  aJewish studies.  aNorth American colleges and universities.  aUS colleges and universities.  aanti-Israel.  aanti-semitism.  aanti-zionism.  aantisemitism.  acollege campus.  acollege journalism.  aeducation.  afree speech.  ahate-speech.  ahostile learning climates.  apersecution.  apublic shaming.  aracism.  areligious intolerance.  asocial justice warriors.  asocial media.  astaged emergencies.1 aBaumann, Fred, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGordon, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLandes, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRomirowsky, Asaf, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThorne, Ashley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relator